      <div xml:id="NA220-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. itu kuṟai nērnta tōḻi talaimakaḷai mukampukkatu.
            2. piṉṉiṉṟa talaimakaṉ ṟōḻi kēṭpat talaimakaḷai ōmpaṭuttatūumām.
            3. tāṉ āṟṟāṉāyc colliyatūumām. (ET: /, but ETv)</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is how the confidante who had granted [HIS] request sought favour with HER.
            2. It is also how the confidante cheered HER up so that HE who was standing behind [her] would hear.
            3. It is also what he said as one who could not bear it.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA220">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            ciṟumaṇi toṭarntu peruṅkaccu niṟīik</l>
<l>            kuṟumuki ḻerukkiṉ kaṇṇi cūṭi</l>
<l>            yuṇṇā naṉmāp paṇṇi yemmuṭaṉ</l>
<l>            maṟukuṭaṉ ṟiritaruñ ciṟukuṟu mākkaḷ</l>
<l>            perituñ cāṉṟōr maṉṟa vicipiṇi </l>
<l>            muḻavukkaṇ pularā viḻavuṭai yāṅka</l>
<l>            ṇūrē meṉṉumip pērē muṟunar</l>
<l>            tāmē yoppura vaṟiyiṟ ṟēmoḻik</l>
<l>            kayalē ruṇkaṭ kuṟumakaṭ</l>
<l>            kayalō rākaleṉ ṟemmoṭu paṭalē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>All too noble indeed</l>
<l>[are] the young(?) little people<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">ciṟu kuṟu mākkaḷ</term>: the first attribute, ciṟu, presumably refers to the age of the people, that is, they are children or youths. kuṟu is a usual attribute for the hill inhabitants, and it might either refer to their being short of stature, or it might be an adjective to <term xml:lang="ta">kuṟavam</term>. (Or is it possible that the name has a semantic meaning, that they are actually called "the short people?)</note> who move about<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tiritaru</term>: <term xml:lang="ta">taru</term> in its usual auxiliary function of an unstoppable movement. <term xml:lang="ta">tiri</term> as a verbal root can either be the intransitive, and then refer to the movement of the people themselves, or the transitive, and then <term xml:lang="ta">mā</term> might be the direct object: they drag the horse along the street, as T.V.G. interprets it.</note> together in the street,</l>
<l rend="indent2">together with us on the good horse that does not eat,<note place="foot">Thus another circumscription of the <term xml:lang="ta">maṭal</term>, the horse made out of palmyra stems.</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">wearing a chaplet of short-budded Yārkkum,</l>
<l rend="indent3">linking the small bells [and] placing the big belt.</l>
<l>[It is] them who are having this great confusion, saying</l>
<l rend="indent3">*we [are] from the village in festival there,</l>
<l rend="indent3">where the eye of the leather-tied drum does not fail*.</l>
<l rend="indent2">If they know [their] custom,</l>
<l>what happens with us means<note place="foot">Taking the <term xml:lang="ta">eṉṟu</term> in the last line not as an absolutive, but as a shorter finite form is one way of making sense of the syntax. T.V.G.’s version is incomprehensible to me.</note> [their] becoming neighbours</l>
<l rend="indent2">to the little woman with carp-like collyrium eyes</l>
<l rend="indent2">[and] sweet words.</l>
            </lg>
      </div>
